##Love Story in Wuhan during the anti-epidemic period: Some people are wandering in the streets, some people are missing in different places

I-CAIJING

The spread of the epidemic, in the eyes of countless people who are still in love or have been in love, as long as it can be safe, is the best celebration

By Liu Yiqin, special correspondent, Caijing, Wuhan

Editor | Yu LE

February 14th is the day many see as a time for a loved one to get together. As of 11:00 am on February 14, the number of newly diagnosed cases of pneumonia in Wuhan had reached 35,991, an increase of 3,910 from yesterday. The epidemic is still spreading, and Wuhan is still under siege.

For those who remain in Wuhan, February 14 this year is the most special. No flowers, restaurants, cinemas, shopping malls closed, pedestrians wearing masks on the road, can not see the expression on his face.

Some lovers are separated because of the epidemic; some lovers can't even meet each other because of the epidemic; some people who once loved each other are separated because of the epidemic; and some people, because of the epidemic, can understand that love is hard to come by.

Wandering Wuhan: "Two people together is enough"

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photograph by Liu Yiqin, Caijing reporter

On the morning of February 11, Yuan Zhi took a hot bath and ate his first meal of rice in more than half a month. He and his wife have been stranded in Wuhan for 18 days and on the streets for five.

On January 23, the day before New Year's Eve, when the city was declared closed, Yuan Zhiqing, a migrant worker in Shenzhen, bought a ticket early in the morning to take his wife home to Shiyan, Hubei Province, for the Lunar New Year, and changed trains in Wuhan. He saw the News said Wuhan to "closed city" , call to ask 12306, customer service told him can transfer, but can not change.

On the morning of January 24, they arrived in Wuhan and were told by station staff that they could not leave Wuhan until the closure was lifted. They could not get in until they called 12306 again.

Since the "city closure" of Wuhan, due to a variety of reasons to stay in Wuhan people are not in the minority. A man from Shanghai returned to his hometown of Chongqing for the Spring Festival, decided to visit friends in Wuhan, and ended up staying in Wuhan. A family of four from Jiangxi came to Wuhan for a road trip years ago A 19-year-old girl from Heilongjiang, accompanied her boyfriend back to Wuhan for Chinese New Year, and then broke up with her boyfriend because of domestic violence after the closure of the city, a person stranded in Wuhan.

Yuan Zhiqing found many people like him stranded in Wuhan at the Tieba and joined the Wechat Group of "people from other parts of Wuhan who are stranded" , which already has more than 230 stranded people, he told Caijing, about half came to Wuhan to visit their families. The other half were migrant workers who had come to change trains, travel or did not have time to leave.

For some to visit relatives or migrant workers stranded, most have a place to stay, and like Yuan Zhiqing, no relatives stranded in Wuhan, temporarily can not find a place to live, only the streets.

As the epidemic continues to spread, nearly all departments in Wuhan are operating at capacity, the city's resources are limited, and most of the hotels that can be operated have been temporarily taken over or requisitioned by the government for the accommodation of medical staff and the isolation of suspected patients, no reservation is accepted even if a room is occasionally available.

In order to get evacuation information nearby, Yuan Zhiqing chose to relocate near Wuhan Tianhe Airport. On January 24, he and his wife checked into a small hotel near the airport, charging 68 yuan a day for a room, every day they can only eat instant noodles or biscuit bread. On February 6, a strange thing happened. The bank card he had been keeping in his bag was gone.

"wechat has always been used to pay, never out of the bank card, " Yuan Zhiqing also very confused, and then he found that because the bank card was frozen, wechat pay also can not pay.

He still had some cash on him to give out to his wife and family. He was also calculating that unsealing the seal was a long way off, and that he would have to pay for food afterwards, rather than spending all his money on accommodation.

On February 6th, he and his wife began to roam. He found an abandoned basement, which was abandoned during the outbreak, and they lived there, charging their phones during the day by finding power in the street at the entrance of a roadside store, and searching the Internet for possible avenues for help.

He called all the contacts he could find, including the mayor's hotline, government departments at all levels, aid stations, 110, and so on. The mayor's hotline's reply was on record, awaiting notification, and the others either said they could do nothing, or give him another contact, and he calls back and is told it's "unfixable. ".

On February 10, Yuan received a phone call informing him that he could check into a rescue hotel in Wuchang District the next day. The hotel is 50 kilometers from where he is. Exhausted, the two of them could no longer walk with their bags in tow. He tried to stop a taxi on the side of the road, but it stopped and offered to take him there for 500 yuan.

He understood that at special times, but the taxi driver did not deliver them to their destination and stopped Wuhan Yangtze River Bridge, five kilometres from their destination, saying they could not cross the bridge and were allowed to get out and go on their own.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
It was already 11 o'clock at night, Yuan Zhiqing and his wife continued to walk, the night temperature dropped very low, but also began to float a small raindrop, they walk 100 meters to sit down for a while.

A kind-hearted volunteer met them, asked about their situation, and offered to take them to the aid station free of charge, and gave them hot food and milk. Staff at the shelter said they would have to wait until the next morning to check in, and the volunteer pleaded with staff to let them sleep in the lobby and make sure they had no fever.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In the early hours of Feb. 11, Yuan finally settled in the hotel lobby. He posted a message to friends, "my birthday gift, " with pictures of food from volunteers and a photo he took of his wife on a Wuhan Yangtze River Bridge.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Yuan Zhiqing, introduced by his family, met his wife. "She's an orphan, and she has some physical defects, " he told Caijing. He didn't know about it at first, but after he found out, he was worried. "She's kind and sensible. "

In Wuhan, wandering these days, he also specialized in teaching his wife to read, occasionally his wife will also be emotional, there are some arguments, fortunately the biggest difficulties have passed, on February 12, he told the "financial" reporter, the aid station also gave them fruit.

On February 13, a reporter from Caijing asked him, do you have any plans for tomorrow? "Two people together is enough, " he said

Break Up Wuhan: "I will not contact with him again"

If I could go back in time, Wang Jingru, a Heilongjiang girl, would never choose Wuhan.

On January 1, Wang arrived in Wuhan with her wuhan-based Boyfriend. Her boyfriend told her that she could stay in Wuhan for a little longer, then go back after the new year, and she agreed. They were staying at a hotel in Wuchang District when the city was declared closed in the early hours of January 23. She did not notice the news until that afternoon, when she was told by friends that she could not leave.

On February 1, she had an argument with her boyfriend, who hit her, and she fell down the hotel stairs and sprained her ankle. She firmly broke up with her boyfriend and said: Don't ever contact him again.

She called 911 right away. The other side tells her, this kind of situation should call woman federation. She called the Women's Federation and received a reply: "Now the epidemic is really serious, we are all in the front line of the donation work, there is really no spare capacity. "

Worried that she was staying here and her boyfriend would come looking for her, he helped her move to another hotel in Hongshan District. After two days, she ran out of money, her parents were unable to provide continued financial support, and she insisted on not contacting her boyfriend.

She has also been calling the mayor's hotline and a helpline for the past few days, but has not been able to get help.

A government worker in charge of the rescue told Caijing that due to the limited resources, they can only select the most difficult groups to give priority to relief through the help line, "One worker receives hundreds of calls a day, and we really can't do it all, " he said

Special period, everything is in overload operation, all the forces are concentrated, priority to help patients, together to fight the epidemic. February 14th, 2020, is a special day, and for the millions of people who still love each other or have loved each other, peace is the best way to celebrate.

Lovesick Wuhan: "never been apart for so long"

It was the 25th day that Dr. Guo Wei and his new wife, Hu Qin, were separated. On January 20, they had their wedding ceremony in their hometown in Huanggang, Hubei Province. The day after the wedding, he returned to Wuhan on duty, and they never saw each other again.

"We've known each other for four years and haven't been apart for more than a week before, " Guo Wei told CAIJING. His wife tried to return to stay with him in Huanggang, but the outbreak was so severe that people were barred from going out to buy anything.

But even if he did make it back to Wuhan, they would hardly see each other, and the front line doctors would be in and out of the wards every day, unable to go home.

Guo Wei's hospital was one of the first designated during the outbreak, and he hasn't left it since he started treating patients with fevers, staying in a hotel across the street from the hospital when he's not on duty.

His wife supported him, and though she worried every day that he wouldn't eat or sleep well, "I know it's his duty. " On New Year's Eve, Hu posted a message on a friend's circle that read: "Go Wuhan! You must be safe. "

Guo Wei doesn't think of himself as a romantic, but during the epidemic he insisted on sending his wife a "love you" every day. "He never used to say such things, " Hu Qin told CAIJING.

One day Guo Wei had to go into the ward on duty, but due to the shortage of supplies, the hospital issued him with a mask is not up to medical standards, just an ordinary dust mask, from the ward out, he was very scared. A few days later, he felt that he should be fine, or told his wife, and received a "scolded. ".

The reason for his anger was not only his concealment, but also his fear. Once, when he saw on the news that all the protective clothing at his hospital had been used up, he panicked and couldn't get through on the phone. "I wanted to help them, but there was nothing I could do but stay home. "

What's the first thing you want to do when this is over? "If you want to go to hotpot together, you'd better travel together, " Guo Wei replied, when Caijing sent the question back to Hu. The response was: "Hug him first, then go to hotpot together. "
